comments.body:
re: https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/pull/31061#discussion_r1878803831

I'm still not sure I see any downsides to adding LIFETIMEBOUND. It seems like a great way to document the fact that these functions require long-lived references, and to provide instant feedback for code and design bugs without needing to create a PR and wait for an ASAN job to fail.

I also don't understand why the additional temporaries and moves and elisions in fad431e548a694600a3fe212127052e5f922a622 would preferable to using references and creating the minimum number of objects with straightforward full-expression lifetimes.

fad431e548a694600a3fe212127052e5f922a622 also seems unsafe because it doesn't prevent lvalues from being passed to the FormatStringCheck constructor, and if an lvalue (or any other argument incompatible with copy elision) is passed it will result in `FormatStringCheck::fmt` being assigned a dangling pointer.

Would suggest following changes as a simpler alternative:

```diff
--- a/src/tinyformat.h
+++ b/src/tinyformat.h
@@ -141,6 +141,7 @@ namespace tfm = tinyformat;
 
 //------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 // Implementation details.
+#include <attributes.h> // Added for Bitcoin Core
 #include <algorithm>
 #include <iostream>
 #include <sstream>
@@ -181,10 +182,8 @@ namespace tinyformat {
 
 // Added for Bitcoin Core. Similar to std::runtime_format from C++26.
 struct RuntimeFormat {
-    std::string fmt; // Not a string view, because tinyformat requires a c_str
-    explicit RuntimeFormat(std::string str) : fmt{std::move(str)} {}
-    RuntimeFormat(const RuntimeFormat&) = delete;
-    RuntimeFormat& operator=(const RuntimeFormat&) = delete;
+    const std::string& fmt; // Not a string view, because tinyformat requires a c_str
+    explicit RuntimeFormat(LIFETIMEBOUND const std::string& str) : fmt{str} {}
 };
 
 // Added for Bitcoin Core. Wrapper for checking format strings at compile time.
@@ -193,7 +192,7 @@ struct RuntimeFormat {
 template <unsigned num_params>
 struct FormatStringCheck {
     consteval FormatStringCheck(const char* str) : fmt{util::ConstevalFormatString<num_params>{str}.fmt} {}
-    FormatStringCheck(const RuntimeFormat& run) : fmt{run.fmt.c_str()} {}
+    FormatStringCheck(LIFETIMEBOUND const RuntimeFormat& run) : fmt{run.fmt.c_str()} {}
     FormatStringCheck(util::ConstevalFormatString<num_params> str) : fmt{str.fmt} {}
     operator const char*() { return fmt; }
     const char* fmt;
```

